File:Katy Perry performing.jpg|thumb|upright|American singer Katy Perry achieved the first number one on the Official Subscription Plays Chart.
The Official Subscription Plays Chart was a music chart based on the number of plays of songs on subscription-based services in the United Kingdom. It was compiled weekly by the Official Charts Company (OCC),<ref>Cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/the-charts-we-compile/|title=The Charts We Compile|year=2010|publisher=The Official Charts Company|location=London|accessdate=9 October 2011|quote=...&nbsp;* Subscription Plays&nbsp;...|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110410221605/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/the-charts-we-compile/|archivedate=10 April 2011|df=dmy-all</ref> until November 2013.<ref>Cite web|url=http://www.telecompaper.com/news/subscription-music-chart-launches-in-the-uk|title=Subscription music chart launches in the UK|date=24 September 2008|publisher=Telecompaper|location=Houten|accessdate=9 October 2011</ref> Each week's number one was published on a dedicated webpage of the OCC's official website<ref>Cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/subscription-plays-chart/|title=Digital Plays Top 40|year=2010|publisher=The Official Charts Company|location=London|accessdate=9 October 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026082309/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/subscription-plays-chart/|archivedate=26 October 2011|df=dmy-all</ref>—this webpage first went live in mid-2009.<ref name=MW2/>

History
The Official Subscription Plays Chart was launched for the first time on 22 September 2008,<ref name=MW1/> for a trial period of six months.<ref>Cite web|url=http://www.kino.de/news/occ-fuehrt-neuerungen-in-den-uk-charts-ein/261590|title=OCC führt Neuerungen in den UK-Charts ein|date=23 September 2008|publisher=Kino.de|location=Munich|language=German|accessdate=9 October 2011</ref> Initially, it was solely based on digital plays from the subscription services HMV, MusicStation, Napster and the Nokia Music Store,<ref>Cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-186665150.html|title=Music Top 500 Chart now tracks online subscriptions.(ONLINE MUSIC SERVICES)|date=26 September 2008|publisher=The Online Reporter|location=Los Angeles|accessdate=9 October 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106112147/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-186665150.html|archivedate=6 November 2012|df=dmy-all</ref> all of which charged users a monthly fee.<ref name=Guardian>Cite news|title=Chart shakeup keeps track with broadband age of music|first=Owen|last=Gibson|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/sep/24/internet|newspaper=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|Guardian Media|location=London|issn=0261-3077|oclc=476290235|date=24 September 2008|accessdate=9 October 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313023653/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/sep/24/internet|archivedate=13 March 2016|df=dmy-all</ref> The data that these services supplied was compiled into a record chart of the 500 most-played tracks—each week also featured top-line market statistics.<ref name=MW1/>

When first launched, the Official Subscription Plays Chart tracked between 3 million and 3.5 million digital plays per week<ref name=MW2>Cite journal|date=6 April 2009|title=World-first as OCC charts ad-supported services|journal=Music Week|publisher=United Business Media|United Business|location=London|issn=0265-1548|oclc=60620772|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storycode=1037410|accessdate=9 October 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120911034536/http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storycode=1037410|archivedate=11 September 2012|df=dmy-all</ref> (with a weekly average of more than 3.2 million), across a library of approximately 340,000 unique tracks.<ref name=MW1>Cite journal|last=Cardew|first=Ben|editor1-first=Paul|editor1-last=Williams|date=22 September 2008|title=OCC launches subscriptions chart|journal=Music Week|publisher=CMP Media|CMP|location=London|issn=0265-1548|oclc=60620772|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storycode=1035555|accessdate=9 October 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230444/http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storycode=1035555|archivedate=3 March 2016|df=dmy-all</ref> The first song to top the chart was "I Kissed a Girl" by Katy Perry. As well as songs that were charting high in the companion UK Singles Chart, the first ever Official Subscription Plays Chart also featured album tracks from records by bands such as Elbow (band)|Elbow, The Verve and Glasvegas.<ref name=BPI/> According to the British Phonographic Industry, "the Official Subscription Plays Chart underlines the greater tendency to experiment among users of subscription services".<ref name=BPI>Cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/press-area/news-amp3b-press-release/article/occ-press-release-7c-music-subscription-services-get-official-chart-2392008.aspx|title=Music subscription services get official chart|date=23 September 2008|publisher=British Phonographic Industry|location=London|accessdate=9 October 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017012142/http://bpi.co.uk/press-area/news-amp3b-press-release/article/occ-press-release-7c-music-subscription-services-get-official-chart-2392008.aspx|archivedate=17 October 2011|df=dmy-all</ref>

In May 2012, the OCC launched the Official Single Streaming Chart|Official Audio Streaming Chart which was (according to the OCC Facebook page) "a much broader panel of the biggest streaming services including Spotify and Deezer. It also counts all audio streams whether that be ad-funded (e.g. free Spotify accounts), and premium subscription account streams."<ref>cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/officialcharts/posts/360447647345246|publisher=OCC|title=The UK's first Official Streaming Chart has arrived!|date=May 10, 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514141047/https://www.facebook.com/officialcharts/posts/360447647345246|archivedate=14 May 2018|df=dmy-all</ref> The two charts ran alongside each other until November 2013 when the Subscription Plays Chart was scrapped and audio streams counted towards the Official Singles Chart from July 2014.

